svg.text: # For this demo, I'm running it on Fedora 34 with kvm2
# Please note the options passed to the minikube start command
# shall be different for each environment.
# Refer to the Minikube documentation for further assistance
# To speed things up on this video, here is the command I used to start my minikube version
# Now let's check if the pods are on the running state.
# It might take a few seconds to get all of them up and running on your end
# For this demo, I'm deploying the awx-operator from the devel branch
# but please refer to the documentation on how deploy a stable release
# Let's wait the container image to be download and the awx-operator
# should be in a running state
# Now first, let's create a AWX instance with using a NodePort service
# This process will take a few minutes to finish, but we should have a
# PostgreSQL statefulset running and a AWX pod with 4 containers in Running state
# In the meantime, you can inspect the awx-operator logs as well
# Allow some time to get the images pulled and for the database migration
# Now that everything is in the running state, we should be good :)
# Let's do a quick test to check if things are looking good
# Let's to visit the NodePort URL using the minikube service command
# Now let's deploy another AWX instance using a NGINX Ingress Controller
# Once we have it in a Running state, we now have an ingress resource created
# With the ingress rule in place, we should be able to access it
# For that, let's add the entry on the
kubectl get ingresses awx-nginx-ingress | grep -v NAME | awk -F' ' '{print $4 " " $3 }'
kubectl get ingresses awx-nginx-ingress | grep -v NAME | awk -F' ' '{print $4 " " $3 }' | sudo tee -a /etc/hosts
# Thanks for watching and happy Ansible automation!
